krt_urine_test_comments: Calcium oxalate dihydrate crystals can be clinically insignificant or an indication of calcium oxalate uroliths in cats and dogs. Formation of calcium oxalate uroliths is often considered idiopathic; however, hypercalcemia, increased dietary oxalates (spinach, nuts, etc.), acidic urine, and highly concentrated urine have been associated with crystal development. The presence of calcium oxalate crystals does not confirm the presence of uroliths; however, abdominal imaging may be warranted. The significance of the calcium oxalate crystals in this case should be determined with consideration of the full clinical history, presentation, and laboratory findings.

In general, struvite crystalluria is most commonly seen with urinary tract infections and less commonly with other urinary changes and in clinically healthy animals. The presence of struvite crystals does not confirm the presence of struvite uroliths. Crystals can be present without uroliths, and vice versa. If clinically indicated, abdominal imaging may be warranted to rule out uroliths. The significance of the struvite crystals should be interpreted in conjunction with the full clinical history, urinalysis, and urine culture.Calcium oxalate dihydrate crystals can be clinically insignificant or an indication of calcium oxalate uroliths in cats and dogs. Formation of calcium oxalate uroliths is often considered idiopathic; however, hypercalcemia, increased dietary oxalates (spinach, nuts, etc.), acidic urine, and highly concentrated urine have been associated with crystal development. The presence of calcium oxalate crystals does not confirm the presence of uroliths; however, abdominal imaging may be warranted. The significance of the calcium oxalate crystals in this case should be determined with consideration of the full clinical history, presentation, and laboratory findings.

The presence of calcium oxalate crystals does not confirm the presence of uroliths; however, abdominal imaging may be warranted. The significance of the calcium oxalate crystals in this case should be determined with consideration of the full clinical history, presentation, and laboratory findings.

In general, struvite crystalluria is most commonly seen with urinary tract infections and less commonly with other urinary changes and in clinically healthy animals (storage artifact). The presence of struvite crystals does not confirm the presence of struvite uroliths. Crystals can be present without uroliths, and vice versa. If clinically indicated, abdominal imaging may be warranted to rule out uroliths. The significance of the struvite crystals should be interpreted in conjunction with the full clinical history, urinalysis, and urine culture.
